Not to criticize, but there's one part you may be overlooking.  The idea of passing a function to setState (vs. just an object with the properties you want to set) is that that you can capture the current state at the moment when setState executes.  I believe React batches setStates so you can't  be sure exactly when they'll execute.  Certainly not necessarily by the time you get to the next line of code.  Anyway, so, instead of checking this.state.seconds in your if, you should do one  setState and send a function that takes care of everything.  So... you could do something like this:


this.setState( prevState => ( 
